{{Infobox person | name = Jennifer Getzinger | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | othername = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|09|26}} | birth_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], U.S. | death_date = | death_place = | alma_mater = | occupation = Film director, script supervisor, television director | years_active = 1993–present | spouse = | children = Theodore Scott Getzinger Esme Rosella Getzinger }}
'''Jennifer Getzinger''' (born September 26, 1967) is an American director and script supervisor of film and television.
For much of her career she worked as a script supervisor on a number of notable films<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/807877/Jennifer-Getzinger/filmography, |title=Jennifer Getzinger filmography |last= |first= |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> including ''[[The Prophecy]]'' (1995), ''[[Phantoms (film)|Phantoms]]'' (1998), ''[[Clay Pigeons]]'' (1998), ''[[Requiem for a Dream]]'' (2000), and ''[[The Devil Wears Prada (film)|The Devil Wears Prada]]'' (2006). She was also script supervisor for the television series ''[[Strangers with Candy]]'', ''[[Sex and the City]]'', ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]'', ''[[The Sopranos]]'', and ''[[Mad Men]]'', making her episodic directorial debut on the latter series.<ref>{{cite web|url= |title=Q&A - Jennifer Getzinger (Director of Episode 5) - Mad Men - AMC |last=Neuman |first=Clayton |publisher=[[AMC (TV channel)|AMCtv.com]] |date=August 28, 2008 |accessdate=June 8, 2011}}</ref> She has been nominated for three [[Directors Guild of America Award]]s for directing the ''Mad Men'' episodes "The Gypsy and the Hobo" (season 3, episode 11; 2009), "The Suitcase" (season 4, episode 7; 2010), and "A Little Kiss" (season 5, episodes 1 & 2; 2012).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.amctv.com/mad-men/2011/01/dga-nomination.php |title=Mad Men's Jennifer Getzinger Nominated for Directors Guild Award |publisher=[[AMC (TV channel)|AMCtv.com]] |date=January 11, 2011 |accessdate=June 8, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115074922/http://blogs.amctv.com/mad-men/2011/01/dga-nomination.php |archivedate=January 15, 2011 |df= }}</ref>
Her other television directing credits include ''[[Hung (TV series)|Hung]]'', ''[[The Killing (U.S. TV series)|The Killing]]'', ''[[Orange is the New Black]]'', ''[[Agent Carter (TV series)|Agent Carter]]'', ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]'', ''[[Shut Eye]]'', ''[[Jessica Jones (TV series)|Jessica Jones]]'', ''[[Outlander (TV series)|Outlander]]'', and ''[[Counterpart (TV series)|Counterpart]]''. In 1998, she directed the independent film ''Blue Christmas'', which was written by her older brother, the late [[imdbname:0004050|Scott Getzinger]]. She also wrote and directed the short film ''Save Me'' in 2006.
Jennifer is the daughter of Mike Warren (''né'' Warren Edwin Getzinger) (1933-2013), the creator and star of the [[Connecticut]] children's TV series ''The Friends of Mr. Goober,'' which was broadcast on WNHC-TV (now WTNH) Channel 8 in [[New Haven]] from 1961 to 1971.<ref>[http://www.nhregister.com/general-news/20091023/mr-goober-to-mad-men "'Mr. Goober' to 'Mad Men" by Joe Amarante, New Haven Register, Oct. 23, 2009]</ref> Warren also hosted ''Connecticut Bandstand'' on WNHC-TV in 1961 and later co-hosted the game show ''[[Dialing for Dollars]]'' on Channel 8 with the late Bob Norman. Warren died November 29, 2013, at age 80.<ref>[http://www.nhregister.com/general-news/20131201/new-haven-tv-personality-mike-warren-dies-at-80 "New Haven TV personality Mike Warren dies at 80," New Haven Register, Dec. 1, 2013]</ref>
