{{Infobox Historic Site | name = St Ursula's| native_name = | image = St Ursula's, Chester.jpg| image_size = 200| caption = St Ursula's| locmapin = Cheshire| map_width = 200| map_caption = Location in Cheshire
| coordinates = {{coord|53.1899|-2.8932|display=inline,title}}
| gbgridref =SJ 404 662| location = 37 Watergate Street,<br>[[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], England| area = | elevation = | formed = | founded = | built = | built_for = | demolished = | rebuilt = | restored = | restored_by = | architect = | architecture = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = | designation1 = Grade I| designation1_offname = | designation1_type = | designation1_criteria = | designation1_date = 28 July 1955| delisted1_date = | designation1_parent = | designation1_number = 1376436| designation1_free1name = | designation1_free1value = | designation1_free2name = | designation1_free2value = | designation1_free3name = | designation1_free3value =  }}

'''St Ursula's''' is a building at 37 Watergate Street, [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], England.  It incorporates a section of [[Chester Rows]] and is recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]] as a designated Grade&nbsp;I [[Listed building#England and Wales|listed building]] because of the quality of the [[undercroft]].<ref name=images>{{NHLE |num= 1376436|desc= Number 37 Street Number 45 Row St Ursulas, Chester|accessdate= 11 April 2015|mode=cs2|ps=none}}</ref>

The building originated somewhere between about 1180 and about 1280.  Alterations were made in the 16th&nbsp;or 17th&nbsp;century and it was largely rebuilt above the Row level in the late 19th&nbsp;century and altered again in the 20th&nbsp;century.  The building is in four storeys.  It is built in [[sandstone]] at the street (undercroft) and Row levels and above this is [[timber framing|timber-framed]].  The undercroft has 5½ bays and it is considered that the walls date from the late 12th&nbsp;century, and are therefore the earliest features yet to have been dated in the structure of the Rows.<ref name=images/>

The undercroft is currently in use as a storeroom for the neighbouring toy shop.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Toycraft|url=http://toycraft.co.uk/index.php/about_toycraft/|publisher=Toycraft|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> 
